DOMAIN_OVERVIEW:
This domain examines methodological approaches to measuring and operationalizing housing cost
burden. Core debate: ratio approach (30/40% of income thresholds) vs. residual income approach
(money left after housing and other necessities). Additional dimensions: objective vs. subjective
burden, before-housing vs. after-housing inequality, normative assumptions embedded in different
measures. Research shows ratio and residual approaches identify different households as burdened,
with residual approach identifying 62% as burdened vs. 48% by traditional measure. Subjective
and objective burden imperfectly overlap, suggesting measurement choice is normatively laden.

RELEVANCE_TO_PROJECT:
Directly tests Hypothesis 6 (housing burden operationalization is normatively charged and affects
findings). Essential for understanding how measurement choices shape conclusions about burden
distribution and policy needs.

KEY_DEBATES:
- Ratio vs. residual income approaches
- Subjective vs. objective burden measurement
- Standard thresholds (30%/40%) vs. context-specific standards
- Normative assumptions in affordability metrics
